article.description: Dominique Canty scored 17 points to lead the Comets over the Sparks 77-51 Saturday night.
article.headline: Sparks lose big to Comets after clinching playoff spot
article.linkText: Sparks lose big to Comets after clinching playoff spot
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- The Houston Comets didn't need Sheryl Swoopes in
the regular season finale against the Los Angeles Sparks.

Dominique Canty scored a season-high 17 points to lead the
Comets over the Sparks 77-51 Saturday night in a matchup of
playoff-bound teams.

Tina Thompson had 13 points and Michelle Snow added 11 for the
Comets (19-15), who will host defending champion Seattle in opener
of the first round on Tuesday.

Los Angeles (17-17) earned the fourth and final postseason spot
in the Western Conference when Phoenix lost at Seattle earlier
Saturday. The Sparks host first-place Sacramento on Wednesday.

Houston, missing Swoopes due to a stomach virus, made nine of
its first 10 shots. Canty, moved from guard to forward just minutes
before tipoff, was 6-for-7 from the floor.

Canty, who added four rebounds and four assists, scored 15
points in an 83-65 win at Washington on July 26.

"Tonight was unbelievable," Canty said. "We just came out
ready to play and they key tonight was our defense. We just kept it
up after they took the big lead early. I know, as a team, we were
motivated to beat them."

Swoopes, who finished the season as the WNBA's leading scorer,
is expected to be in uniform Tuesday.

"She has a stomach virus and is dehydrated," said Comets head
coach Van Chancellor. "They thought the best thing for her to do
is not play today. We think she'll be ready for Tuesday night."

Lisa Leslie scored nine points to lead the Sparks, winners of
their previous three meetings with the Comets. Los Angeles avoided
its worst-ever loss to the Comets when Mwadi Mabika hit a 3-pointer
just before the game ended.

"We came out a little flat today," Sparks head coach Joe
Bryant said. "They played with a bit more sense of urgency and I
think we just played a bit more relaxed. We needed the game (a win
at San Antonio) last night. That was an important game."

Houston opened the game with a 12-4 lead and then used an 11-0
run to break the game open early in the first half.

Thompson started the run by hitting an open jump shot and Snow
capped it with a pair of free throws with 13:48 left in the half.

Rookie center Sancho Lyttle was perfect from the floor in the
first half, making all three of her shots, and scored seven points
in a five-minute span late in the period. She finished with 11
points on 4-of-5 shooting overall.

"Tonight we just played like it didn't matter who got the
shots," Chancellor said. "We lose Sheryl Swoopes tonight, but
Canty played great and Lyttle was good with 11 points and eight
rebounds."

The Sparks tied team records for fewest points in game and
fewest point in the first half and Comets set their season-high
with an 18-point margin of victory.

"We played slow tonight," Leslie said. "You have give Houston
credit because they came out and jumped on us. They shot the ball
really well. I think we tried to get back in it, but in the
playoffs we just have to play our style of basketball."
